{
  "text": "The psychomotor effects of the drugs used in this study have been previously assessed. In a healthy volunteer study, FMP (fentanyl 50 \u00b5g, midazolam 2 mg and propofol 35 mg, per 70 kg body weight) induced impairment on a DSST, which, at 75 minutes after drug administration, was comparable to that caused by a blood alcohol concentration of 0.11% (greater than twice the legal limit for driving in Australia) [CITATION_1] . No impairment was detected at 180 minutes after drug dosing. Their subjects were younger and drug doses were lower than the ones we used. The midazolam component of the FMP combination appears the key drug producing prolonged psychomotor impairment [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The psychomotor effects of N 2 O appear to closely correlate with its kinetics [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In two separate studies involving healthy volunteers, after inhalation of 30% N 2 O for 35 and 40 minutes, psychomotor performance had returned to baseline by 5 and 22 minutes respectively [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . In another report, after self-administration of 50% N 2 O by patients having colonoscopy, psychomotor performance had returned to baseline by 30 minutes following the end of the procedure [CITATION_9] . Psychomotor performance, assessed on a DSST, after inhalation of a sevoflurane sub-anaesthetic concentration of 0.6% for 35 minutes by volunteers was shown to be impaired at 5 but not at 30 minutes after the end of administration [CITATION_10] . Our results are in accord with these findings.",
  "correct_citation": {
